  "prompt": "How are confidence intervals used?",
  "response": "Confidence intervals are used in statistics to:\n\n1. Estimate population parameters\n- Provide a range of likely values for a population characteristic\n- Indicate the precision of an estimate\n\n2. Statistical inference\n- Determine the reliability of sample-based estimates\n- Assess the likelihood that a true population parameter falls within a specific range\n\n3. Hypothesis testing\n- Support or challenge research claims\n- Evaluate statistical significance of findings\n\n4. Decision making\n- Help researchers and professionals make informed choices\n- Provide uncertainty measures for critical decisions\n\n5. Research reporting\n- Communicate statistical uncertainty\n- Show the range of plausible values for a measurement\n\n6. Quality control\n- Monitor manufacturing processes\n- Assess variability in production metrics\n\n7. Risk assessment\n- Evaluate potential outcomes in finance, healthcare, and other fields\n- Quantify uncertainty in predictions\n\n8. Comparing groups\n- Determine if differences between groups are statistically significant\n- Assess overlap or separation of confidence intervals\n\n9. Predictive modeling\n- Provide bounds for potential future outcomes\n- Indicate the reliability of forecasts\n\n10. Academic and scientific research\n- Standard method for reporting statistical findings\n- Demonstrate the robustness of research conclusions\n\nConfidence intervals help quantify uncertainty and provide a more nuanced understanding of statistical estimates.",
